ce:section.ce:para:
This work is intended to complement previous efforts to investigate SDG interlinkages (e.g. [8,9•
                     ,10,11]) by ‘drilling down’ on a single target. Griggs et al. [8] analyze the interaction between SDGs 2, 3, 7 and 17 and other SDGs at the target-level. They use expert judgement and a seven point scale to rank the importance and direction of the interactions. UN-Water [10] ‘highlight[s] the interdependency between the targets under Goal 6 … and other Goals and targets …’ Using expert judgement, links (interlinkages) are identified and classified as either a ‘main synergy’ or causing a ‘potential conflict’. Scharlemann et al. [11] use expert judgement to analyze the interactions among all goals (at the goal level) and color-code the interactions according to the relative influence of one goal on another. The accent of their analysis is on human–environment interactions. Pradhan et al. [9•
                     ] take a different approach to the other cited studies and perform a statistical analysis of historical SDG indicator data (on the country-scale and global scale) to uncover synergies and trade-offs between SDGs. As compared to these studies, the present work focuses on a single target and uses evidence from the literature to articulate interlinkages between water quality and other SDGs. It complements the review of Ezbakhe [12] by examining many other aspects of water quality interlinkages including their scale, their classification, the issue of indicators, and how to minimize trade-offs.
